%[text] # **2D concentration map**
%[text] **Creation of a 2D concentration map**
%[text] While a field desorption map only shows a hit map of ions on the detector, without distinguishing between differing ions, the 2D concentration map is created by means of a pos file with ions already allocated. Therefore, the ranged mass spectrum and an allocated pos file are prerequisites for the creation of such a map.
%%
%[text] ## **Creation of bin vectors**
%[text] As distance variable (*dist*) two coordinates have to be selected. The *bin* variable must contain the bin width for both binning directions. It determines the resolution of the resulting 2D concentration map. Different bin widths are possible.
dist = [pos.y, pos.z]; % selection of the distance variables to be binned %[control:dropdown:1b98]{"position":[9,21]}
bin = [1 1]; % bin width in x and y direction %[control:editfield:7e5d]{"position":[8,11]}
mode = 'distance'; % 'distance' is the only possible mode in 2D and 3D
[binCenters, binEdges] = binVectorsFromDistance(dist,bin,mode); % creates bin centers and bin edges of the voxels
  %[control:button:5203]{"position":[1,2]}
%[text] 
%%
%[text] ## Voxelisation of the data set
%[text] In the next step, the voxelisation will be performed based on the bin edges. Each 'voxel' represents in 2D actually a pixel (*pix*).
%[text] The *startIdx* and *endIdx* values define the selection of ion hit indices the user wants to contribute to the creation of the cell array *pix*.
startIdx = 1; % start hit index  %[control:editfield:9bf9]{"position":[12,13]}
endIdx = 10; % end hit index, must be greater than startIdx %[control:editfield:2a80]{"position":[10,12]}
pix = posNdBin(pos(startIdx:endIdx,:),dist(startIdx:endIdx,:),binEdges); % creates a cell array of various pos subsets, representing the voxelisation of the pos variable
  %[control:button:3b1d]{"position":[1,2]}
%[text] 
%%
%[text] ## Creation of an anonymous function
%[text] In the next step, a so-called 'anonymous function' will be defined. This means that a function handle will be created, here it is called *concentrationKernel*. By doing so, in a subsequent step the here defined function can be applied on many elements of a cell array.
%[text] As input, the detector efficiency is needed. For example, in case of the LEAP 4000X HR, this value is 0.37 or 37 %, respectively.
%[text] The inputs *excludeListConc* and *volumeName* are optional:
detEff = 37; % detector efficiency, input as decimal or percentage figure possible %[control:editfield:1f8f]{"position":[10,12]}
excludeListConc = {'unranged'}; % list of ions that shall not be considered for the concentration calculation, unranged atoms appear as 'unranged', optional %[control:editfield:357e]{"position":[19,31]}
volumeName = 'test'; % name of the volumes, parsed as character array, optional %[control:editfield:7f63]{"position":[14,20]}
concentrationKernel = @(pos) posCalculateConcentrationSimple(pos,detEff,excludeListConc,volumeName);
  %[control:button:8811]{"position":[1,2]}
%[text] 
%%
%[text] ## Calculation of the concentrations
%[text] In the following section, the concentration (and also count and variance) for all not excluded species are calculated for each pixel. This is done with MATLAB's function *cellfun*. This command applies the function *func* to the contents of each cell of the cell array *cell*.
%[text] NOTE: The bin size (specified in the first section) has a huge impact on the computing time of this command. Bin sizes of 1 to 2 nm seem rather reasonable.
func = concentrationKernel; % specification of the function to be applied on cell array
cell = pix; % specification of cell array
conc = cellfun(func,cell,'UniformOutput',false); % calculation of concentration for each cell/pixel
  %[control:button:31ea]{"position":[1,2]}
%%
%[text] In order to create a heat map for a specific species, the wanted species must be defined (see edit field in next code line).
wantedSpecies = cellfun(@(pos) pos.Al(pos.format == 'concentration'),conc); %[control:editfield:8c1a]{"position":[36,38]}
figure; %[output:4d92f18d]
concentrationMap = imagesc(binCenters{1},binCenters{2},wantedSpecies); % creates image of the concentration map of the specified species %[output:4d92f18d]
axis equal; %[output:4d92f18d]
  %[control:button:2c68]{"position":[1,2]}

